On Arch Linux, you have three main ways to install VS Code. The "best" one depends on whether you want the official Microsoft features (like the full Marketplace and Live Share) or a pure open-source experience.

1. The Official Microsoft Version (AUR)
This is the most popular choice. It is the exact same binary you'd get from Microsoft's website, meaning it includes the official Marketplace and proprietary features.

Since it's in the AUR (Arch User Repository), you'll need an AUR helper like yay or paru.

Using yay:

Bash
yay -S visual-studio-code-bin
2. The Open Source Version (Official Repo)
Arch maintains an open-source build called code in the extra repository.

Pros: Easy to install with pacman; fully open-source.

Cons: It uses the Open VSX registry instead of the Microsoft Marketplace (some extensions might be missing), and it lacks some proprietary branding.

To install:

Bash
sudo pacman -S code
3. VSCodium (Privacy Focused)
If you want VS Code but want to strip out all Microsoft telemetry and tracking, VSCodium is the way to go.

Using yay:

Bash
yay -S vscodium-bin
Comparison at a Glance
Feature	visual-studio-code-bin	code (OSS)	vscodium
Source	AUR	Official Repos	AUR
Marketplace	Official Microsoft	Open VSX	Open VSX
Telemetry	Enabled (can opt-out)	Minimal	Removed
Live Share	Works	Needs manual fixes	Needs manual fixes
Quick Tip: If you just installed Arch and don't have an AUR helper yet, you can install the official version manually like this:

Bash
sudo pacman -S --needed base-devel git
git clone https://aur.archlinux.org/visual-studio-code-bin.git
cd visual-studio-code-bin
makepkg -si
