Yes, it really is that simple! Those four lines are the standard "manual" way to install any AUR package. And since visual-studio-code-bin is the official branded version, you can log in with your Microsoft account to sync your settings, use Copilot, and access the full Marketplace—exactly like you would on Windows or macOS.

As for the safety of the AUR (Arch User Repository), your skepticism is actually a sign that you're a good Arch user. Here is the breakdown of the risk:

Is it "Safe"?
In the world of Arch, "safe" is a relative term. Unlike the official repositories (installed via pacman), the AUR is unvetted community content. Anyone can upload a script.

However, visual-studio-code-bin is one of the most popular packages in the entire ecosystem.

The "Many Eyes" Effect: Because thousands of people use it, any malicious change to the script would likely be spotted and reported within minutes.

Transparent Scripts: When you run those 4 lines, you are running a PKGBUILD. This is just a text file (a bash script). It doesn't contain the app itself; it just tells your computer: "Go to Microsoft's servers, download the official .deb or .tar.gz file, and move the files to the right folders on Arch."

Why would you "Risk" it?
The "risk" isn't usually that someone hacked the app; it's that the person maintaining the script might have a typo or, in a nightmare scenario, added a line to steal data.

How to be 100% safe:
Before you run makepkg -si in that folder, type:

Bash
nano PKGBUILD
Look for the source= line. If it points to https://update.code.visualstudio.com/... or another official Microsoft domain, you’re good. You aren't trusting a random person; you're just using their script to go fetch the "real" thing from Microsoft.

Summary: Why people use the AUR version
The MS Account Log-in: Only this version and the Flatpak/Snap versions support the official Microsoft "Sync" and proprietary extensions (like the C# Dev Kit or certain Debuggers) without jumping through hoops.

Official Marketplace: You get the "real" extension store, not the open-source alternative (Open VSX).

If you are comfortable with those 4 lines, you’ve essentially mastered the manual way to use the AUR. Most users eventually install a tool like yay to automate those 4 lines into a single command, but doing it manually first is the best way to understand what's happening under the hood.

