and using yay, it would basically just be downloading a script containing those 4 lines?

Exactly! You've got it. yay is essentially a high-speed robot that performs those manual steps for you so you don't have to keep doing the "Git Clone Shuffle" every time there's an update.

Here is exactly what yay does when you type yay -S visual-studio-code-bin:

1. The Search & Fetch
Instead of you going to the AUR website and copy-pasting a URL, yay talks to the AUR API, finds the package, and clones the repository into a temporary cache folder (usually ~/.cache/yay/).

2. The "Security Check" (Optional but Recommended)
By default, yay will ask if you want to "CleanBuild" or "Diff menu".

If you select the Diff menu, it shows you exactly what changed in the PKGBUILD script since the last version. This is where you can verify that the source= URL still points to Microsoft and hasn't been changed to hacker-site.ru/virus.tar.gz.

3. Dependency Solving
This is where yay earns its keep. If VS Code required five other obscure tools from the AUR to run, yay would find them, download their scripts, build them in the right order, and install them. Doing that manually is a massive headache.

4. Running the Script
Finally, yay runs the same commands you saw earlier:

It calls makepkg to download the official files from Microsoft.

It packages them into an Arch-compatible format (.pkg.tar.zst).

It hands that package over to pacman to actually install it on your system.

Why use yay instead of the 4 lines?
Updates. This is the big one.

The Manual Way: To update VS Code, you have to remember it exists, navigate back to that folder, run git pull, and then run makepkg -si again.

The yay Way: You just type yay (with no arguments). It checks every AUR package you’ve ever installed, sees if Microsoft released a new version, and updates them all at once alongside your normal system updates.

The Verdict: Stick to the 4 lines for your first time just to feel the "Arch power," but once you're tired of manual updates, install yay and let the robot do the heavy lifting.

Since you're worried about safety, just make a habit of glancing at the PKGBUILD when yay offers the "Diff menu"—it’s the Arch version of "reading the terms and conditions," except people actually do it!


